If you're tagging well-known or popular music, this is a great app that's fast, relatively easy to use and accurate.    But...if you're an EDM fan, or happen to hear something really new or something really old and pretty obscure, Shazam will do a much better job of correctly giving you a result you can use later.  For example, on SiriusXM's Alt Nation, if they play a new song by some emerging artist, Soundhound won't find the result for a week or two of the tune being SXM's rotation.  Shazam does almost every time.  They could improve the Spotify interface inside the app, and give users the ability to directly add a song tagged in Soundhound to a Spotify playlist.  Bottom line,  get both Shazam and Soundhound and you'll get 99.5% of the tunes you want to remember tagged.

I was having an issue with no songs being recognized. I went in to Options for the appliction and then went to the Port setting and changed it to port 80. I played a random song and did a search with SoundHound and the second try it found the song. I then went back into Options and changed the port setting back to 443 and did several searches and SoundHound hit 9 out of 10 so the app appears to be working again. I am waiting to hear back from the Dev team on the issue. It could be that I recently updated to Jelly Bean 4.2.1 which reflashed the radio causing stale connections to the SoundHound servers but not sure as of yet.  Update - Reply from Dev  Thank you for being a part of the SoundHound community. Some carriers modify the information SoundHound sends from your device, and this prevents SoundHound from working properly. SoundHound now automatically attempts to send the information in a way that will not be modified by the carrier. But, you can also manually change the setting if you are still having trouble. Go to the options page by launching SoundHound and then click Menu > Options >  Port Settings, then select 80, or if this does not work, select 443.

Once upon a time, not long ago, SoundHound was much better than Shazam. It accurately identified all the popular songs I tagged (similar to Shazam) as well as just about all the Indie/little-known songs that Shazam couldn't. But somewhere around 2 or 3 months ago, everything changed. SoundHound is now incapable of accurately identifying all the Indie/little-known songs that Shazam accurately indentifies. What the hell happened? As an Android user who never had an iPhone (on which Shazam famously burst onto the social scene) I always prided myself on the fact that, while Shazam made more noise socially, SoundHound for Android was easily better at tagging songs, both popular and Indie. But that's not the case anymore. For the past few months, every little-known song I try to tag with SoundHound fails to be identified; conversely, those exact same songs are ALWAYS indentified by Shazam. A lot of the songs are from commercials, but even a song by Hot Chip (Ends of the Earth from their new album, In Our Heads) went unidentified by SoundHound after numerous attempts to tag it. Meanwhile, Shazam identified the song immediately on the first try. What happened, SoundHound?

I want to use this app to help me identify songs that are playing in MY earshot, and NOT to tell me what other people are currently Soundhound'ing, Listening to, or Tweeting about.  At this point in my short history with Soundhound, I'm debating just how much I actually need it, with this irritating development. I considered it a lucky find last year when it was on the Android Market cheapo-giveaway; now, I'm less enamoured.  I'm scoring this average, as it DOES still help me identify songs I hear but don't know, but past version have been superior.

The very first song I tried with Shazam (Touch - Tea Party) it could not recognize it in two tries, loaded up the free version of SoundHound, got it in about 2 seconds. The next day, the paid version of SoundHound was on sale, a no-brainer purchase. Another thing to add, I work retail and we have music playing throughout the store, with the speakers about 20 feet up in the air, not loud, just enough for background music, SoundHound is still able to pickup and identify the music with all the other ambient sounds going on (shoppers talking, etc.), amazingly well done app.
